(precise edge of what their predictive system can hold before it fails. That moment) Tj T*
(is not an accident. It is an engineering problem, and the material you are working) Tj T*
(with is the human brain.) Tj T*
(Every brain in your audience is running the same core process: generating) Tj T*
(probabilistic predictions about what is about to happen, and then comparing those) Tj T*
(predictions to what actually occurs. The gap between prediction and reality ? the) Tj T*
(prediction error ? is where experience lives. Wonder is not what happens when) Tj T*
(something impossible occurs. Wonder is what happens when the prediction fails at a) Tj T*
(moment of maximum confidence, in a context the nervous system has determined is safe.) Tj T*
(This book is about engineering those conditions deliberately.) Tj T*
(What You Have Felt Before) Tj T*
(You are watching a performance and you know something is coming. You can feel it ?) Tj T*
(not the specific content, but the shape of the approach. The buildup is) Tj T*
(unmistakable. Your attention has narrowed, your breathing has slowed slightly, and) Tj T*
(you are tracking everything the performer is doing with a kind of focused pleasure) Tj T*
(that is slightly uncomfortable. The impossible moment, when it arrives, is not a) Tj T*
(surprise exactly. It is a fulfillment. But of what? Of a prediction you were) Tj T*
(building toward without knowing its destination. That structure ? the confident) Tj T*
(build toward an unresolvable outcome ? is the core architecture of wonder.) Tj T*
(The Setup Is the Performance) Tj T*
(There is a persistent misconception in performance: that the reveal is where the) Tj T*
(work happens. That the dramatic moment at the end is the performance and everything) Tj T*
(before it is the runway. This gets it backwards. The reveal is the receipt. The) Tj T*
(setup is the performance.) Tj T*
(Consider what the audience experiences during a strong build. Their dopamine system) Tj T*
(is fully active. The salience network is engaged. Attention is narrowed and focused.) Tj T*
(The prediction machine is running at high confidence, which means the violation ?) Tj T*
(when it arrives ? will have maximum impact. All of that is happening before the) Tj T*
(reveal. The reveal simply releases the tension the build created.) Tj T*
(Now consider what happens when performers invert this: delivering the reveal first,) Tj T*
(then explaining what happened. The prediction never got built. There was nothing to) Tj T*
(violate. The impressive thing happened and then got explained. The result is) Tj T*
(admiration at best. Wonder requires the setup.) Tj T*
(Expectation Loading) Tj T*
(The deliberate construction of a specific confident prediction before the moment) Tj T*
(that violates it. The more precisely you specify what the audience expects, the) Tj T*
(greater the force of the departure. Vague setups produce vague impact. Specific) Tj T*
(setups produce specific astonishment.) Tj T*
(Earned Completion) Tj T*
(The performer seeds a detail early, the audience holds it as unresolved) Tj T*
(significance, and the later payoff creates deep coherence. The sensation is not) Tj T*
(surprise ? it is recognition.) Tj T*
(What to call it: Expectation Loading. The deliberate construction of a specific) Tj T*
(confident prediction before the moment that violates it. The more precisely you) Tj T*
(specify what the audience expects, the greater the force of the departure from it.) Tj T*
(Performer's Note) Tj T*
(Most performance failures happen before the reveal. A reveal that does not land is) Tj T*
(almost never a problem with the reveal. It is a problem with the build. Before you) Tj T*
(redesign the ending, redesign the thirty seconds before it.) Tj T*
(· · ·) Tj T*
