(The Five Forces of Salience) Tj T*
(What makes the brain say this matters? Understanding the salience network is) Tj T*
(understanding attention itself.) Tj T*
(????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????) Tj T*
(What You Have Felt Before) Tj T*
(You are at a networking event. The room is exactly what it is: glasses clinking,) Tj T*
(five conversations happening simultaneously, people scanning over each other's) Tj T*
(shoulders for whoever else is in the room. Movement everywhere. And then your eyes) Tj T*
(move ? not because you decided to look. You look before you decide. Something across) Tj T*
(the room has shifted the calculation. Then you find it: a person who has done almost) Tj T*
(nothing except become still. Shoulders relaxed. Chin level. Not scanning for) Tj T*
(approval. They appear, in the middle of all that motion and noise, as though they) Tj T*
(already belong here in a way the rest of the room does not quite achieve. People are) Tj T*
(looking twice.) Tj T*
(The anterior insula and dorsal anterior cingulate cortex form the brain's) Tj T*
(priority-detection system. This is the salience network, and it determines what you) Tj T*
(consciously attend to out of the roughly eleven million bits per second of sensory) Tj T*
(information your nervous system is receiving. Five forces reliably trigger it:) Tj T*
(1. Novelty) Tj T*
(The brain is not interested in the familiar. Familiarity produces habituation ? the) Tj T*
(nervous system stops allocating resources to processing things that are predictable.) Tj T*
(Novelty does the opposite: it triggers a full orienting response, pulling) Tj T*
(attentional resources away from whatever else is competing for them and directing) Tj T*
(them toward the novel stimulus. This is why your opening cannot be what they have) Tj T*
(seen before.) Tj T*
(2. Emotional Relevance) Tj T*
(The amygdala continuously evaluates incoming information for personal significance ?) Tj T*
(particularly for threat or reward. Information that has emotional stakes gets) Tj T*
(prioritized. Information that is emotionally neutral does not. This is why a reading) Tj T*
(that connects to something true in the participant lands more powerfully than the) Tj T*
(same words delivered to a stranger. Personal stakes upgrade the signal.) Tj T*
(3. Social Signal) Tj T*
(The brain is a social organ. It devotes enormous processing resources to the) Tj T*
(evaluation of other people ? their status, their intentions, their emotional state,) Tj T*
(and what their behavior means for our own safety and belonging. A performer who) Tj T*
(understands social signal design can commandeer this processing priority reliably.) Tj T*
(4. Unresolved Uncertainty) Tj T*
(The brain cannot tolerate open loops. The Zeigarnik effect ? the psychological) Tj T*
(tendency to better remember interrupted tasks than completed ones ? demonstrates) Tj T*
(that an unresolved question continues to occupy working memory long after you have) Tj T*
(nominally moved on from it. The brain compulsively orients toward unresolved states,) Tj T*
(which is why a well-built mentalism routine feels almost physically uncomfortable at) Tj T*
(its peak. The audience cannot look away because the prediction machine is screaming) Tj T*
(for resolution and it has no off switch.) Tj T*
(5. Contrast) Tj T*
(Change is more salient than content. The brain's change-detection systems flag) Tj T*
(transitions, not sustained states. A whisper after loud speech. Stillness after) Tj T*
(movement. Warmth after clinical precision. Dark after light. This is why the) Tj T*
(performer who speaks softly in a room accustomed to loud presentations commands more) Tj T*
(attention than the one who out-performances everyone else. The contrast is the) Tj T*
(signal.) Tj T*
(Stacking the Forces) Tj T*
ET

endstream
