(Your opening 60 seconds should engage at least three of the five simultaneously.) Tj T*
(Contrast \(silence\) + Social Signal \(direct eye contact\) + Novelty \(unexpected) Tj T*
(action\) creates an attentional lock most rooms cannot resist.) Tj T*
(Common Misread) Tj T*
(If the room does not go quiet in the first ten seconds, you are not commanding) Tj T*
(attention ? you are competing with background noise for it. These are categorically) Tj T*
(different situations. The first gives you the room. The second puts you in a fight) Tj T*
(you have already started losing.) Tj T*
(Performer's Note) Tj T*
(Design your opening 60 seconds to hit at least three of the five forces) Tj T*
(simultaneously. Start with contrast \(silence\), add social signal \(direct eye) Tj T*
(contact\), then novelty. Do not wait to earn the room. Claim it. If the room does not) Tj T*
(go quiet in the first ten seconds, your opening is competing with background noise.) Tj T*
(Redesign it around the five forces, not around what you find interesting to perform.) Tj T*
(· · ·) Tj T*
() Tj T*
(CHAPTER 3) Tj T*
(Tension, Threat and the Window of Wonder) Tj T*
(Not all tension is equal. The difference between wonder and fear is the finest line) Tj T*
(in performance.) Tj T*
(????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????) Tj T*
(What You Have Felt Before) Tj T*
(You are watching a performance and it becomes slightly uncomfortable. Not in a bad) Tj T*
(way ? in a way where you are almost holding your breath, where the person next to) Tj T*
(you has gone very still, where the room has shifted into something more focused and) Tj T*
(more private than a few minutes ago. That is productive tension. That is wonder) Tj T*
(working at its upper edge. You know precisely when it tips over ? when the same) Tj T*
(feeling becomes not exciting but just uncomfortable, when you want it to resolve not) Tj T*
(because you are invested but because you need relief. You know it instinctively. You) Tj T*
(probably cannot say how you knew.) Tj T*
(And there is another experience, probably familiar: watching a performer hold) Tj T*
(tension past the point where the room can enjoy it. You can feel the audience) Tj T*
(receding. The room that was leaning forward starts to lean back. And then ? not) Tj T*
(because anything funny happened ? someone laughs. It is not a genuine laugh. It is a) Tj T*
(pressure release. A nervous system discharging tension it can no longer hold) Tj T*
(comfortably. That is a cortisol discharge event. The window has been exceeded.) Tj T*
(The Cortisol Threshold) Tj T*
(Cortisol is the primary stress hormone. It is released in response to perceived) Tj T*
(threat, and it produces a cascade of physiological changes designed to prepare the) Tj T*
(body for action: heightened alertness, narrowed attention, elevated heart rate,) Tj T*
(suppressed non-essential systems. In moderate doses, in a context where the nervous) Tj T*
(system has determined that the threat is not real, cortisol enhances attention and) Tj T*
(memory encoding. This is productive tension. The audience is alert, focused, and) Tj T*
(emotionally engaged.) Tj T*
(When cortisol levels exceed the threshold the context can justify, the experience) Tj T*
(tips from exciting to aversive. The audience is no longer choosing to stay in the) Tj T*
(feeling ? they are managing it. The performance contract has been violated, not) Tj T*
(because the content was wrong, but because the physiological experience was not) Tj T*
(matched by sufficient safety cues. Moderate cortisol enhances memory encoding. High) Tj T*
(cortisol combined with helplessness disrupts hippocampal function and degrades) Tj T*
(memory. The goal is excitation, not stress. They feel similar from inside the) Tj T*
(moment. They produce very different outcomes the next morning.) Tj T*
ET

