(The window can be recovered. This is the most important thing a performer can know) Tj T*
(about cortisol: the damage is not permanent in the moment, and the tools for) Tj T*
(recovery are not complicated. But they require the willingness to recognize what has) Tj T*
(happened and respond to it rather than push through.) Tj T*
(The standard mistake when a room tips over the window is to accelerate ? to perform) Tj T*
(harder, give them more, make the next moment bigger. This loads more cortisol onto a) Tj T*
(nervous system already at capacity. The right response is social: step briefly out) Tj T*
(of the performance, make human contact, and let the room's nervous system normalize) Tj T*
(before you resume the build.) Tj T*
(The Reset Sequence) Tj T*
(Step slightly out of performance mode ? a shift in register, not a full break.) Tj T*
(Warmer, slightly more casual. Look at a specific person and say something that) Tj T*
(acknowledges the room rather than performing at it. Give them thirty seconds of) Tj T*
(normal human interaction. The cortisol drops. You resume. The build is still there.) Tj T*
(Productive Silence) Tj T*
(Three to five seconds of genuine stillness ? not awkward void ? is a cortisol) Tj T*
(modulator. It signals: I am comfortable in this moment. Nothing is wrong. The room) Tj T*
(reads the performer's comfort in silence as safety data. If the performer is calm,) Tj T*
(the room recalibrates toward calm.) Tj T*
(The Redirect) Tj T*
(A piece of misdirection that invites the audience to think about something external) Tj T*
(? a detail about the volunteer, a brief observation about the room ? briefly) Tj T*
(suspends tension rather than building it. A few seconds of directed external) Tj T*
(attention lets the cortisol level settle before you reload the build.) Tj T*
(Audience Variability and the Moving Threshold) Tj T*
(Corporate rooms that have been in a day-long conference arrive with elevated) Tj T*
(baseline cortisol ? decision fatigue, social performance pressure, the low-grade) Tj T*
(tension of professional evaluation. Their window for additional productive tension) Tj T*
(is narrower than a fresh audience. You have less room to build before they tip.) Tj T*
(Design accordingly: shorter build sequences, more frequent social releases, a first) Tj T*
(effect that earns the room rather than challenges it.) Tj T*
(Evening events where alcohol is present are physiologically different rooms.) Tj T*
(Moderate alcohol reduces the amygdala's threat-detection sensitivity ? which means) Tj T*
(the room's floor is lower, but so is its ceiling. You can hold more without tipping) Tj T*
(because the threat response is blunted. But you also get less from the window: the) Tj T*
(emotional encoding that happens inside productive tension is partially disrupted,) Tj T*
(which means the memory impact of the performance is reduced. More fun in the room.) Tj T*
(Less remembered the next morning.) Tj T*
(High-status rooms ? executives, government audiences, professional specialists ?) Tj T*
(have more developed suppression behavior. They have been trained across careers to) Tj T*
(not visibly display cortisol response. This makes them harder to read using the) Tj T*
(standard indicators. The signal is still there; it is smaller. Watch) Tj T*
(micro-expression and self-soothing rather than gross body behavior.) Tj T*
(Performer's Note) Tj T*
(The window is the most important variable you cannot design in advance. You can) Tj T*
(design for the average ? calibrated from the brief you received, the event context,) Tj T*
(the room's constitution. But the actual threshold is in front of you when you start,) Tj T*
(and it moves as the show proceeds. Every technique in this book works inside the) Tj T*
(window. Almost nothing works reliably outside it.) Tj T*
