(The Gorilla Principle) Tj T*
(In 1999, Daniel Simons and Christopher Chabris published one of the most cited) Tj T*
(papers in attention research. Participants watched a video of two teams passing a) Tj T*
(basketball and were asked to count the number of passes made by one team. While they) Tj T*
(counted, a person in a gorilla suit walked through the scene, paused, and walked) Tj T*
(out. Approximately half of participants failed to notice the gorilla entirely ? not) Tj T*
(because they were not paying attention, but because they were paying maximum) Tj T*
(attention to the wrong thing. This is inattentional blindness: the failure to) Tj T*
(perceive something clearly visible when full attention is engaged elsewhere. For) Tj T*
(performers, this is not interesting. It is foundational.) Tj T*
(The audience is not failing to protect themselves from your method. They are) Tj T*
(allocating cognitive resources to the narrative you have given them, and the) Tj T*
(narrative is consuming what would otherwise be available for peripheral monitoring.) Tj T*
(Your job is not to move faster than their eyes. Your job is to build a story) Tj T*
(compelling enough that their eyes never go looking.) Tj T*
(The Octopus Principle) Tj T*
(A mind given too many simultaneous suggestions handles none of them deeply. One or) Tj T*
(two high-quality, emotionally charged suggestions focused on a single outcome) Tj T*
(produce dramatically stronger results than a volley of technique. Concentrate the) Tj T*
(suggestion before you deliver it.) Tj T*
(Change Blindness) Tj T*
(People regularly fail to notice large changes to objects they are looking at) Tj T*
(directly when those changes occur during a brief visual interruption ? a blink, a) Tj T*
(cut, a glance away. Change detection requires attention, not just vision. They are) Tj T*
(different systems.) Tj T*
(System 2 Load Test) Tj T*
(Before every performance: is the story genuinely demanding? Does it require real) Tj T*
(cognitive investment from the audience? A story that can be followed passively) Tj T*
(leaves excess attentional capacity for peripheral monitoring. A story that requires) Tj T*
(tracking and prediction does not.) Tj T*
(Psychological Marking) Tj T*
(There is a technique so elemental that it operates without the audience noticing it) Tj T*
(is in use, and often without the performer noticing they are using it. Psychological) Tj T*
(marking is the act of placing deliberate, repeated attention on a specific object,) Tj T*
(location, or person in a way that causes the audience to unconsciously assign it) Tj T*
(significance. Not through gesture or misdirection toward it, but through what might) Tj T*
(be called a casual yet intentional distinction ? you treat it differently, even) Tj T*
(slightly, from everything else in the environment. You touch it once more than the) Tj T*
(others. You hesitate a fraction longer when you look at it. You let your gaze return) Tj T*
(to it between actions.) Tj T*
