(CHAPTER 17) Tj T*
(The Behavioral Training Framework) Tj T*
(Most corporate training fails not because the content is wrong but because the) Tj T*
(learning architecture is misaligned with how the brain actually changes behavior.) Tj T*
(????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????) Tj T*
(Declarative instruction ? presenting information in lectures or slides ? activates) Tj T*
(cortical learning systems but does not reliably produce the emotional encoding) Tj T*
(necessary for behavioral change. To change a behavior, you need to create an) Tj T*
(experience that the hippocampus tags as significant. A slide deck reliably does not) Tj T*
(do this.) Tj T*
(The Design Sequence) Tj T*
(Every conceptual learning objective should be preceded by a direct experience that) Tj T*
(makes the concept visceral and personal before the explanation arrives. The) Tj T*
(explanation is not the learning moment. The experience is. The explanation provides) Tj T*
(the framework to understand what just happened.) Tj T*
(The experience-first sequence: create a direct experience ? allow genuine confusion) Tj T*
(or surprise ? introduce the framework that explains what just happened ? support) Tj T*
(application. Run it in reverse and you produce knowledge without behavior change.) Tj T*
(Reverse it once and participants will remember the concept but not apply it.) Tj T*
(The Design Sequence) Tj T*
(Experience ? Reflection ? Framework ? Application. Run it in reverse and you produce) Tj T*
(knowledge without behavior change.) Tj T*
(The Hippocampus Test) Tj T*
(For a learning moment to be retained, the hippocampus needs an emotional tag. The) Tj T*
(question to ask about every training activity: will this generate genuine surprise,) Tj T*
(genuine recognition, or genuine discomfort? If not, it will not be remembered.) Tj T*
(The Opening Experience) Tj T*
(The opening experience needs to meet three criteria: it must be visceral enough that) Tj T*
(intellectual observation is temporarily not possible, it must relate directly to the) Tj T*
(behavioral concept being taught, and it must generate genuine ? not performed ?) Tj T*
(emotional response. Surprise works. Cognitive dissonance works. Mild physical or) Tj T*
(social discomfort works, when handled with care.) Tj T*
(The most reliable opening experience in behavioral influence training is a) Tj T*
(demonstration of involuntary compliance ? showing participants that their own) Tj T*
(behavior has been shaped by environmental design they did not notice. The moment of) Tj T*
(recognition ? the moment they realize they were led without knowing it ? produces) Tj T*
(the precise combination of surprise, curiosity, and mild self-directed discomfort) Tj T*
(that the hippocampus tags most reliably for long-term retention.) Tj T*
(The Performer Advantage) Tj T*
(Most trainers simulate primary experience through case studies and role-play. A) Tj T*
(performer who demonstrates the learning objective on the participants creates real) Tj T*
(experience. Retention rates for primary vs. simulated experience differ) Tj T*
(significantly. Source: Kolb \(1984\), Experiential Learning.) Tj T*
(· · ·) Tj T*
() Tj T*
