(Referral Psychology) Tj T*
(People refer performers to protect their own reputation. They refer someone they) Tj T*
(trust to make them look smart for the referral. Build trust the whole way through ?) Tj T*
(not just onstage ? and the referrals follow without asking.) Tj T*
(The Seven Items on the Limbic Ledger) Tj T*
(The Limbic Ledger is not a metaphor. It is a description of how emotional memory) Tj T*
(actually works: not as a neutral record of events, but as a continuously updated) Tj T*
(evaluation of how an experience ? and the person responsible for it ? made you feel.) Tj T*
(The client's limbic system has been running this assessment from the moment they) Tj T*
(first encountered you. The performance is one data point. Here are the others.) Tj T*
(1. The First Email) Tj T*
(The first point of contact establishes the frame. An email that reads as) Tj T*
(professional, unhurried, and specific to their situation tells the limbic system:) Tj T*
(this person is a peer. An email that reads as eager, overly accommodating, or) Tj T*
(template-issued tells it: this is a vendor. The frame is established before you have) Tj T*
(demonstrated anything about your performance. It is almost impossible to fully) Tj T*
(override in the room.) Tj T*
(2. The Response Lag) Tj T*
(How long you take to respond to a booking inquiry is a signal, whether you intend it) Tj T*
(to be or not. Same-day response signals availability in the wrong direction.) Tj T*
(Two-to-three business days signals that you are working at a level where requests) Tj T*
(come in.) Tj T*
(3. The Pre-Show Conversation) Tj T*
(What you ask about before the show tells the client what you think matters.) Tj T*
(Performers who ask only about logistics are signaling that the logistics are the) Tj T*
(professional concern. Performers who ask about the audience, the organizational) Tj T*
(context, the thing the client wants the room to walk away feeling ? this tells the) Tj T*
(limbic system that the person they have hired is thinking about the same thing they) Tj T*
(are thinking about.) Tj T*
(4. The Arrival) Tj T*
(How you arrive at the venue is observed before you have spoken to anyone. The) Tj T*
(performer who arrives unhurried, engages with staff naturally, and does not perform) Tj T*
(an air of importance broadcasts differently than the one who arrives harried or who) Tj T*
(navigates the building with visible anxiety.) Tj T*
(5. The Logistics Ease) Tj T*
(Every logistical complication costs a small amount of limbic credit. Not because the) Tj T*
(complication is large, but because friction is always read by the nervous system as) Tj T*
(a signal about whether something is going to be easy or hard. The performer whose) Tj T*
(production requirements are clear, self-sufficient, and handled without drama scores) Tj T*
(on this item.) Tj T*
(6. The Recovery) Tj T*
(Something will go wrong. A technical failure, a late start, a volunteer who does not) Tj T*
(cooperate as expected, a moment that does not land. The recovery is observed more) Tj T*
(carefully than the performance. A performer who handles the unexpected with genuine) Tj T*
(composure earns more from that moment than from any planned effect.) Tj T*
(7. The Follow-Through) Tj T*
(What comes after the performance is the last item the limbic system scores, and it) Tj T*
(is the most differentiating. A specific, personal thank-you ? naming something that) Tj T*
(happened in that room ? tells the client that the attention you brought to the stage) Tj T*
(was not a performance. It was who you are.) Tj T*
(Seven items. The performance is assumed. The list is what surrounds the performance,) Tj T*
(and what determines whether the performance becomes a long professional relationship) Tj T*
