(The Rule of Compression) Tj T*
(The higher-status your positioning, the less explaining it needs. Weak authority) Tj T*
(needs paragraphs. Strong authority needs a sentence.) Tj T*
(Why Most Bios Fail) Tj T*
(Most performer bios are written like defensive résumés. They stack credentials, list) Tj T*
(appearances, and throw in everything impressive. Somehow, after all that effort,) Tj T*
(they still feel flat. Because most bios are written from the performer's insecurity) Tj T*
(rather than the client's psychology. The client is not trying to confirm that you) Tj T*
(are good. They are trying to reduce the risk of being wrong.) Tj T*
(The bio structure in four moves: Position \(what you are in a way that places you at) Tj T*
(the right level\) ? Distinction \(what makes your work different\) ? Proof \(selected,) Tj T*
(specific, brevity-tested evidence\) ? Relevance \(connect to this client or reader\).) Tj T*
(Weak vs. Strong Testimonial) Tj T*
(WEAK: 'Chris was amazing and everyone loved him.' STRONG: 'Chris held a room full of) Tj T*
(skeptical executives for an hour and had them fully engaged within minutes.' The) Tj T*
(second one does the buyer's job for them.) Tj T*
(What Testimonials Are Actually For) Tj T*
(A testimonial is not peer validation. It is borrowed certainty for a buyer who has) Tj T*
(not seen you yet. Every testimonial should reduce a specific concern a buyer would) Tj T*
(have. If it does not reduce a concern, it is decorating, not selling.) Tj T*
(Performer's Note) Tj T*
(Let the client's voice carry the weight. Your own voice delivering your own) Tj T*
(credentials is the least persuasive version of the same information. Use your) Tj T*
(materials to create the frame. Use your clients' words to confirm it.) Tj T*
(· · ·) Tj T*
