(deception cues ? is only possible once a baseline is established. Without it, change) Tj T*
(is invisible.) Tj T*
(6.  Calibration  The process of establishing what is normal for a specific person) Tj T*
(before interpreting shifts in their behavior. The foundation of all behavioral) Tj T*
(profiling. Cannot be shortcut.) Tj T*
(7.  Change Blindness  The failure to notice significant changes to a scene when they) Tj T*
(occur during a brief visual interruption ? a blink, a cut, a glance away. Change) Tj T*
(detection requires attention, not just vision. They are different systems.) Tj T*
(8.  Compliance  Behavioral conformity driven by external pressure. Distinct from) Tj T*
(internalization. It lasts as long as the authority is present. The goal in) Tj T*
(behavioral training is internalization, not compliance.) Tj T*
(9.  Cortisol  The primary stress hormone. Released in response to perceived threat.) Tj T*
(In moderate doses in a safe context, enhances attention and memory encoding. In) Tj T*
(excess, disrupts hippocampal function and degrades memory formation. The cortisol) Tj T*
(window is the central concept of Chapter Three.) Tj T*
(10.  Inattentional Blindness  Failure to perceive something clearly visible when) Tj T*
(attention is fully occupied elsewhere. Simons and Chabris \(1999\) showed that half of) Tj T*
(participants failed to notice a person in a gorilla suit walking through a scene) Tj T*
(they were actively watching. For performers, this is not interesting. It is) Tj T*
(foundational.) Tj T*
(11.  Neural Simulation Process  The mechanism by which observers simulate the) Tj T*
(internal states of people they are watching ? activating both when performing an) Tj T*
(action and when observing the same action in another. The mechanism by which a) Tj T*
(volunteer's emotional state broadcasts to the room. Manage one, and you are managing) Tj T*
(both.) Tj T*
(12.  Predictive Processing  The dominant contemporary model of brain function: the) Tj T*
(brain continuously generates and updates probabilistic predictions about incoming) Tj T*
(sensory information, and responds most strongly to prediction errors ? moments where) Tj T*
(reality departs from expectation.) Tj T*
(13.  Salience Network  The neural network ? primarily the anterior insula and dorsal) Tj T*
(anterior cingulate cortex ? responsible for detecting what matters in the) Tj T*
(environment. The five forces of salience \(novelty, emotional relevance, social) Tj T*
(signal, unresolved uncertainty, contrast\) are the primary activators.) Tj T*
(14.  Thin Slicing  The ability to make accurate, stable judgments about a person or) Tj T*
(outcome based on a very brief observation of behavior. Established by Ambady and) Tj T*
(Rosenthal \(1992\). The scientific foundation of the performer's claim that rapid) Tj T*
(human reading is possible and real.) Tj T*
(15.  Zeigarnik Effect  The tendency to better remember interrupted tasks than) Tj T*
(completed ones. Incomplete goals and open questions occupy working memory until) Tj T*
(resolved. The neurological engine of sustained attention in a performance context.) Tj T*
() Tj T*
(Dopamine    A neurotransmitter central to the brain's reward and anticipation) Tj T*
(system. Dopamine neurons fire in response to cues that predict reward, not the) Tj T*
(reward itself. The implication for performance: the build is the neurobiologically) Tj T*
(active phase, not the reveal. Source: Schultz, Dayan & Montague \(1997\), Science,) Tj T*
(275\(5306\), 1593?1599.) Tj T*
(Embodied Emotion    The principle that physical posture and gesture partially) Tj T*
(constitute emotional states rather than merely expressing them. A room of people) Tj T*
(standing experiences a different emotional reality than a room seated. Behavioral) Tj T*
(choices shape internal experience.) Tj T*
(Social Proof    The tendency to determine appropriate behavior by observing what) Tj T*
(others are doing, especially under uncertainty. The mechanism behind standing) Tj T*
ET

